<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
In our phylogenetic analysis, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Y. H. Pi &amp; Q. R. Li" authorityYear="2021" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Xylariaceae" genus="Nemania" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Nemania rubi" order="Xylariales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="rubi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Nemania rubi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
formed a distinct branch, which is sister to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. changningensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="changningensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">N. changningensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. caries" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="caries">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">N. caries</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. RAxML tree based on analysis of a combined dataset of ITS, Î±-actin, rpb 2 and Î²-tubulin sequences from taxa of Nemania and related genera. Bayesian posterior probability (PP) â¥ 0.90 is marked at the node and the maximum likelihood bootstrap support (BS) values greater than â¥ 75 %; a dash (&quot; - &quot;) indicates a value &lt;0.90 (PP) or &lt;75 % (BS). The strain number is indicated after the species name. The here-studied strains are in bold and new species are indicated in red." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.69906.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/581027" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">1</figureCitation>
). In morphology, 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. rubi" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="rubi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">N. rubi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. caries" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="caries">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">N. caries</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinct in having a long-cylindrical apical apparatus and the inequilateral ascospores lacking a germ slit (
<bibRefCitation author="Miller, JH" journalOrPublisher="University of Georgia Press, Athens" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" refId="B27" refString="Miller, JH, 1961. A Monograph of the World Species of Hypoxylon. University of Georgia Press, Athens" title="A Monograph of the World Species of Hypoxylon." year="1961">Miller 1961</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1127/0029-5035/2002/0074-0075" author="Ju, YM" journalOrPublisher="Nova Hedwigia" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="75 - 120" refId="B19" refString="Ju, YM, Rogers, JD, 2002. The genus Nemania (Xylariaceae). Nova Hedwigia 74: 75 - 120, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1127/0029-5035/2002/0074-0075" title="The genus Nemania (Xylariaceae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1127/0029-5035/2002/0074-0075" volume="74" year="2002">Ju and Rogers 2002</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, the perithecia of 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. caries" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="caries">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">N. caries</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are obovoid (0.3-0.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ã">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-0.7 mm) and its height is greater than the width (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mycres.2007.01.009" author="Tang, A" journalOrPublisher="Mycological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" pagination="392 - 402" refId="B41" refString="Tang, A, Jeewon, R, Hyde, KD, 2007. Phylogenetic relationships of Nemania plumbea sp. nov. and related taxa based on ribosomal ITS and RPB2 sequences. Mycological Research 111: 392 - 402, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mycres.2007.01.009" title="Phylogenetic relationships of Nemania plumbea sp. nov. and related taxa based on ribosomal ITS and RPB 2 sequences." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mycres.2007.01.009" volume="111" year="2007">Tang et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The ascomata surface of 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. rubi" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="rubi">
